article.description:
Florida traveled all the way from the swamp 
to the desert only to get blown out by New Mexico's best night of 
basketball this season.
article.headline: Lobos shine in rout of Gators
article.linkText: Lobos shine in rout of Gators
article.story:
TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Florida traveled all the way from the swamp
to the desert only to get blown out by New Mexico's best night of
basketball this season.

Jana Francis scored a career-high 25 points on 10-of-14 shooting
and the 11th-seeded Lobos blew open a 24-point halftime lead in an
83-59 romp over the fifth-seeded Gators on Saturday night in the
first round of the NCAA tournament.

Katie Montgomery matched her career best with 21 points, 14 in
the first half when she made four of five 3-pointers to help the
Lobos to an overwhelming 48-24 lead at the break. Dionne Marsh
added 18 points for the Lobos.

"We played with confidence and intensity," New Mexico coach
Don Flanagan said. "Those two things are important. It doesn't
matter the opponent if you are playing like that."

If New Mexico (22-9) can knock off defending NCAA champion
Baylor in the second round on Monday night, the Lobos will advance
to the regional semifinals to be played on their home court in
Albuquerque.

"We're just not ready to go home yet," Francis said. "We have
to come out with this same intensity Monday night."

Dalila Eshe scored 17 and Danielle Santos 15 for the Gators
(21-9), who shot 34 percent and were under 30 percent most of the
night. New Mexico shot 51 percent.

"We knew they were talented," said Florida's Sarah Lowe. "We
didn't come out with the focus and composure we needed against a
team like that."

Inconsistency has plagued the Gators all season. In the final
four games of the regular season, they won at Tennessee and beat
LSU at home, but lost one-sided contests to Auburn and South
Carolina.

New Mexico, cheered on by a big following that made the trek
from Albuquerque, didn't exactly come in on a roll, either. The
Lobos were 5-5 over their previous 10 games, including a 57-45
first-round loss to UNLV in the Mountain West Conference
tournament.

New Mexico topped that point total by halftime. Its 48 points
was a season high for a half.

The Lobos shot 57 percent (17-for-30) in the first half,
compared with 29 percent (8-for-28) for the Gators.

The Lobos took control for good with a 17-2 run that gave them a
28-12 lead on Marsh's soft jumper in the lane with 7:21 left in the
half. The outburst grew to 28-6 and the lead reached 39-16 after
Montgomery's 3-pointer with 4:42 to go in the half.

The Gators trailed by as many as 30 and never got closer than 20
in the second half.

It was a rematch of a first-round NCAA game two years ago.
Florida won that one on New Mexico's home court.

The Lobos, in their fifth consecutive NCAA tournament appearance
and sixth overall, advanced to the second round for the second
time. The other came in 2003, when they made it to the regional
semifinals.
